WINDOWS Only:

The Raiseon plugin (affectionately nicknamed "raisin") is a Windows-specific tool designed to solve a focus restriction in the Windows operating system that prevents minimized windows from raising or focusing themselves automatically.
Note: This is not part of the Gajim package as it was deemed "too complicated" for the task, yet no one has or will produce a simpler version. It is offered here as your only option.

    Trigger: When Gajim detects a new incoming message, the plugin briefly changes the Gajim window title.
    
    AHK Detection: A background AutoHotkey script (included as gajim.ahk) monitors for this specific title change.

    Window Raising: Once the script identifies the modified title, it forcefully restores and focuses the Gajim window for the user.

    Reset: After the window is visible, the title is changed back to "Gajim" to reset the process for the next message. 

Usage Requirements
To use this setup, you need:

    The Raiseon plugin installed in Gajim's plugin directory (typically C:\Users\USERNAME\AppData\Roaming\Gajim\Plugins on Windows).
    An active AutoHotkey installation to run the .ahk script.
    The gajim.ahk script running in your system tray to listen for the title trigger. 

    enable the plugin in Gajim and run the .ahk script (optional: make a shortcut to the script in your windows startup dir) 
